<article>
    <h1>Work lounges</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201220/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-20"><time>2020-12-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>This was the year al­most ev­ery­one worked from home – or lived at work, de­pend­ing on whom you ask.</p>
    <p>To cater to those go­ing stir-crazy from be­ing at home 24/7, ho­tels, cin­e­mas and even Jewel Changi Air­port have turned un­derused restau­rants, bars and lounges into co-work­ing spa­ces, of­fer­ing a seat, power plug and speedy Wi-Fi for as lit­tle as $15 a day. Many pack­ages come with snacks and free-flow cof­fee and tea, just like an of­fice pantry.</p>
    <p>With their af­ford­able day rates, th­ese lounges of­fer flex­i­bil­ity – the big­gest perk.</p>
    <p>Got a meet­ing in town? Head to Yo­tel Sin­ga­pore’s mod­ern restau­rant-cum-bar Komyu­niti, which comes with gen­er­ous meal cred­its.</p>
    <p>Need to run er­rands? The concierge at Or­chard Ho­tel will store your be­long­ings for the af­ter­noon if you are work­ing at the</p>
    <p>Lobby Lounge. Park­ing is in­cluded.</p>
    <p>And if you are hit with a se­vere case of the post-lunch food coma, pop by Golden Vil­lage at Sun­tec City be­tween noon and 3.30pm for a nap in its Gold Class cin­ema, which you can pur­chase as a top-up to its Zest@Gold Class lounge cowork­ing pack­age.</p>
    <p>When the pan­demic abates, re­mote-work­ing ar­range­ments are likely here to stay. For those who need a change of en­vi­ron­ment, th­ese lounges are just the thing to fill the gap.</p>
    <p>Clara Lock</p>

